INT. FIRST PLAINS BANK, BROKEN BOW, NEBRASKA - DAY

Fluorescent light, carpet tiles, one teller window open. A cardboard
sign on an easel by the door: THE STEWARDSHIP ACT — WORKING FOR
COMMUNITIES LIKE YOURS. Nobody is looking at it.

CRICKET DAWES, 79, sits in the waiting area. Pressed white shirt,
buttoned to the collar. A manila folder square on his knees, both
hands on it.

A LOAN OFFICER, 30s, tie too new, opens his office door.

OFFICER:
Mr. Dawes? Sorry about the wait.

INT. LOAN OFFICE - CONTINUOUS

Cricket sits. Sets the folder on the desk, turned so it faces the
officer. The officer wakes his monitor.

OFFICER:
How's the morning treating you?

CRICKET:
Fine.

OFFICER:
Good. That's — good.

He opens the folder. County letterhead on top. He reads, and his face
does the thing people's faces do when they already know.

CRICKET:
County reassessed in March. Four thousand two hundred six dollars,
due the fifteenth. I have two thousand one hundred.

OFFICER:
Okay.

CRICKET:
I'm asking for six months.

The officer types. Reads his screen. Types again.

OFFICER:
So — the hardship extension program. That's the one that would fit
you. It's showing "suspended pending federal review." That came down
in January with the new remittance rules. It's not us, it's the—

He stops himself. Turns the monitor a few inches toward Cricket.

CRICKET:
The screen says no.

OFFICER:
The screen says no.

He scrolls. Stops. Squints at something.

OFFICER:
Mr. Dawes, this deposit line — you receive a quarterly direct deposit
from NASA. Of zero dollars and zero cents.

CRICKET:
Clerical thing. Fifty years now.

OFFICER:
Every quarter? They send you nothing? On purpose?

CRICKET:
Regular as the light bill.

The officer looks at the entry a moment longer. The account
description field reads: DAWES, E. — ASTRONAUT (ACTIVE).

OFFICER:
It has your occupation as—

CRICKET:
It's old.

The officer looks at Cricket. Cricket looks back, level. It is not
his business, and the officer decides so.

OFFICER:
Right.

He pulls a form from the drawer. Fills a line. Stamps it, then
re-inks the stamp and stamps a date box twice, hard.

OFFICER:
I can log your paperwork as received next cycle. That gives you sixty
days before it's delinquent. It's not six months. It's what I've got.

CRICKET:
Sixty days.

OFFICER:
I'm sorry it's not more.

Cricket stands. Squares the folder under his arm. Puts out his hand.
The officer shakes it.

CRICKET:
You did what the screen let you.

Cricket goes. The officer sits back down, pulls the monitor back to
face him, and looks at the zero-dollar deposit line for a moment.
Then he closes the file.

EXT. FIRST PLAINS BANK, PARKING LOT - DAY

Cricket sits in his pickup, folder on the bench seat, keys in his
hand. Through the windshield: the courthouse across the square, and
above it, the flag, moving.

He watches it one moment. He starts the truck.

CUT TO:
